body:
This is really a very minor nice-to-have, and I no longer even need it, so feel free to ignore.

I was looking at using a dispatch object to encapsulate the state of some background computation, something like:

``` javascript
function backgroundComputation() {
  return d3.dispatch("start", "stop")
      .on("start", /* Start some complex computation here… */)
      .on("stop", …);
}

// Without this change, worker would be undefined.
var worker = thing().on(…).start();

// Later, e.g. if a button is pressed…
worker.stop();
```

It turns out I needed to support other, non-event operations, so I ended up using d3.rebind instead, so got chaining for free anyway.

If you think it's worth it, I can add some tests too.

I suppose one argument against this is you might want to return something like the number of listeners that were notified instead.

Included a new `d3.pluck` function to easily obtain an array of values from a common property in a list of objects or nested arrays. This is extremely useful when computing domains for example, since it avoids the need for custom map functions.

Additionally it also allows to define a default value as third argument to be returned in the case that the given property is not defined in some of the nested objects.

```
var data = [ {x:100, y:'Sp'}, {x:120, y:'Uk'}, {x: 60, y:'Fr'}, {y: 'Gr'} ];
xScale.domain([0, d3.max(d3.pluck(data, 'x', 0))]);
yScale.domain(d.pluck(data, 'y'));
//xScale.domain([0, d3.max(data, function(d){ return d.x; })]);
//yScale.domain(data.map(function(d){ return d.y; }));
```
